 of class literals, like `Array<String>::class.java`. It seems that Kotlin allows this, but there's confusion about parameterized types in class literals. To avoid issues, using `arrayOf<String>()::class.java` could be a safer choice for runtime class retrieval.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering Reflection in Java**\\n\\nI'm pondering the use of `java.lang.reflect.Array.newInstance(String::class.java, 0).javaClass as Class<Array<String>>`. It seems like a complicated approach, and I’m wondering if it’s considered bad practice or just a reflection in testing scenarios. The idea of direct reflection might not be appropriate here, and I'm questioning whether there might be a cleaner or more straightforward way to achieve the same goal. I need to think about the implications and whether this could lead to any potential issues in my code.\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Added a dedicated Kotlin test file for the active dynamic-access class:\n\n- `tests/src/org.jetbrains.kotlin/kotlin-main-kts/2.3.21/src/test/kotlin/org_jetbrains_kotlin/kotlin_main_kts/PlexusXmlBeanConverterTest.kt`\n\nCoverage added for `PlexusXmlBeanConverter` dynamic-access paths:\n\n- Array conversion via XML to reach `Array.newInstance`\n- Text conversion through a public `String` constructor to reach `Class.getConstructor` and `Constructor.newInstance`\n- XML bean implementation loading through:\n  - thread context class loader\n  - role/default class loader fallback\n  - `Class.forName` fallback with bootstrap-loaded role class\n- Bean instantiation paths reaching `Class.newInstance`\n\nI did not run or compile tests, per instruction. Note: the working tree already contains unrelated metadata/resource changes that I did not touch.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0378865b2074cf1d0169fa353a43c0819783213f0ff07ccf89\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 719, "output": 972, "cacheRead": 4147